of payments tied to fluctuating revenues.You give WaterStation money and it=
 gives you a fixed return of 28%. Where does it get the money to pay your 2=
8% returns? WaterStation=E2=80=99s answer is apparently =E2=80=9Cfrom selli=
ng lots of filtered water to customers,=E2=80=9D but 352 suggests that the =
answer is =E2=80=9Cfrom new investors, like a Ponzi scheme.=E2=80=9DActuall=
y 352=E2=80=99s proposed explanation is far more baroque than that.=C2=A0It=
s story is that=C2=A0the franchisees got their payments not (just) from new=
 franchisees but from=C2=A0a $100 million bond offering. And the main buyer=
 of the bonds was 352 Capital, which bought the bonds because its portfolio=
 manager was secretly also a WaterStation franchisee who wanted to get his =
Ponzi payments and who saw his own fund=E2=80=99s clients as the best way t=
o get the money.In 352=E2=80=99s telling, Jordan Chirico, who managed the 3=
52 fund for Leucadia Asset Management (a division of Jefferies), was also a=
