8, before he joined Leucadia. He joined Leucadia in 2020 to start the 352 f=
und, investing in asset-backed securities. And in 2022, =E2=80=9CChirico ar=
ranged for the 352 Fund and its affiliate to invest in Water Station Manage=
ment through a bond offering.=E2=80=9D In this offering, WaterStation sold =
$56.3 million of Class A bonds to another investor (Heartland Financial), a=
nd $15 million of Class B bonds to 352. The money was supposed to be used t=
o acquire more water machines, and the machines would be collateral for the=
 bonds.=C2=A0Chirico allegedly didn=E2=80=99t tell anyone at Jefferies that=
 he was a WaterStation franchisees. Also his friends and family were franch=
isees.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CWater Station Management failed to make payments with =
regard to these Chirico-related franchise holdings,=E2=80=9D and so =E2=80=
=9CChirico personally paid them a total of $300,000 for the purpose of serv=
icing their debts and discouraging them from commencing litigation against =
Water Station Management and Wear.=E2=80=9D Also somehow =E2=80=9CKaiwing F=
ung (=E2=80=98Fung=E2=80=99), the former Head of Credit for the 352 Fund, a=
lso failed to adequately disclose that he owned Water Station Management fr=
anchises at the time of the 352 Fund=E2=80=99s investment.=E2=80=9D Chirico=
 led =E2=80=9Ca three-person (later four-person) team=E2=80=9D at 352, and =
two of them were also WaterStation franchisees.Anyway the money allegedly d=
id not go to buy water machines:By no later than August 2023, REVL [Capital=
 Management, the collateral manager for the bond]=C2=A0knew that thousands =
of Water Station Machines allegedly purchased with the bond proceeds did no=
t exist and that millions of dollars of bond proceeds had not been used by =
Water Station Management for their intended purpose. REVL attempted to perf=
orm a physical inspection of the machines that Water Station Management cla=
imed both to own and to use as collateral for the bonds. REVL determined th=
at 163 of the 164 machines in its sample set for inspection did not exist. =
REVL then discovered that more than 3,000 machines that were supposed to be=
 operating in Family Dollar stores, and=C2=A0in other locations, were =E2=
=80=9Cactually missing.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6There was (or should have been) n=
o doubt, by at least August 2023, that Water Station Management was perpetr=
ating a fraud. To this point, Water Station Management had been submitting =
to REVL purchase orders and invoices for the purchase of Water Machines, al=
l to convince REVL to authorize the release of bond proceeds for those purc=
hases=E2=80=94but those machines did not exist. The purchase orders and inv=
oices were falsified. The collateral and revenue reports that purported to =
show the machines were installed and generating revenue were likewise fabri=
cated. On information and belief, instead of purchasing and operating Water=
 Machines, Water Station Management used the bond proceeds primarily to pay=
 =E2=80=9Cfranchisees=E2=80=9D their guaranteed returns on their =E2=80=9Ci=
nvestment,=E2=80=9D or to buy out franchisees who had raised complaints abo=
ut the business=E2=80=94a classic Ponzi scheme. Because Chirico was owed mo=
ney in connection with his =E2=80=9Cinvestment=E2=80=9D in the scheme, and =
his friends and family were likewise =E2=80=9Cinvestors,=E2=80=9D he stood =
to directly, personally benefit from these payouts.Seems bad.=C2=A0But =E2=
=80=9CREVL only reported what it discovered to Wear and Chirico,=E2=80=9D w=
hich makes a sort of sense: WaterStation was the debtor, 352 was the credit=
or, and if WaterStation was defrauding 352 then the people to notify would =
be WaterStation and 352. It=E2=80=99s just that the=C2=A0person=C2=A0at 352=
 who got the notification was allegedly in on the scheme.=C2=A0Actually tha=
t is oversimplified: There was another creditor involved, Heartland Financi=
al, who owned the Class A bonds and who does not seem to have anything to d=
o with the alleged scheme. That was inconvenient for the alleged Ponzi, so =
Chirico allegedly had 352=C2=A0buy them out:Then, in December 2023, despite=
 being fully aware of the ongoing fraud at Water Station Management, Chiric=
o made the inexplicable decision to cause the 352 Fund and its affiliate to=
 buy out the Class A bondholder at a purchase price of $57.6 million. There=
 was no legitimate business or investment rationale for quadrupling the exp=
osure of the 352 Fund to Water Station Management when Chirico knew that Wa=
ter Station Management was committing a fraud, and that the bonds were unde=
rcollateralized by tens of millions of dollars (if not more). On informatio=
n and belief, one contributing factor to Chirico=E2=80=99s decision was to =
remove any oversight by the Class A investor, which would allow him to loos=
en the indenture=E2=80=99s restrictions and requirements for the benefit of=
 Water Station Management, and direct further funds from the 352 Fund to Wa=
ter Station Management to prop up the failing company and the ongoing Ponzi=
 scheme.And, right,=C2=A0that is how a Ponzi works: There are always some i=
nvestors who want their money back, or who get suspicious, or who=C2=A0migh=
t=C2=A0get suspicious, and the way to solve that problem is to raise some m=
oney from new investors to kick out the suspicious ones. And Chirico had ac=
cess to a good supply of new investors: He ran a=C2=A0bond fund that could =
provide the money.Somehow Jefferies has Chirico=E2=80=99s texts with his wi=
fe sort of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0saying =E2=80=A6=C2=A0this?Indeed, in a September=
 2023 text message exchange with his wife, who was a co-owner of C3 Capital=
, Chirico expressed that he was =E2=80=9Cpissed at Ryan [Wear]=E2=80=9D bec=
ause =E2=80=9Che=E2=80=99s not going to be able to make our 300k payment on=
 time either from selling C3 so need to address that as well.=E2=80=9D When=
 his wife asked, =E2=80=9CDoes that worry you about the bond deal,=E2=80=9D=
 Chirico responded: =E2=80=9CYes for bond deal but I care as much or more a=
bout the personal investors that are with him still =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D (Emp=
hasis added).Still needed more money though:By no later than January 2024, =
Water Station Management was insolvent and unable to meet basic day-to-day =
funding obligations, including making payroll. REVL had confirmed that thou=
sands of Water Machines that were supposed to have been purchased with bond=
 proceeds were =E2=80=9Cmissing.=E2=80=9D In a January 2024 telephone call =
with Wear and his CFO, [Tyler] Sadek, Chirico (who recorded the call) ackno=
wledged that the 352 Fund=E2=80=99s $87.9 million bond investment was under=
collateralized by at least $46 million. On that call, Sadek admitted this w=
as =E2=80=9Cthe largest franchise fraud in the history of the United States=
=E2=80=9D and told Wear that he =E2=80=9Cwas going to jail.=E2=80=9D Notwit=
hstanding his having knowledge of the fraud, and on information and belief =
in furtherance of that fraud, Chirico directed the 352 Fund to upsize the b=
ond offering and, in February 2024, provided Water Station Management with =
an additional $19 million of funds.=C2=A0If you do a due diligence call wit=
h a company, and the company=E2=80=99s chief financial officer tells=C2=A0i=
ts chief executive officer, on a recorded line, that he is going to jail,=
=C2=A0and you hear that and your reaction is=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe need to buy e=
ven more of those bonds=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean part of me wants to =
say =E2=80=9Cyou are a bold contrarian risk-taker and a lot of asset manage=
rs would want to hire you.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s coolness under pressure =
right there. But yes another possibility is that you are in on the scam.If =
you believe 352=E2=80=99s allegations, then obviously WaterStation and Chir=
ico look bad, but Jefferies and Leucadia don=E2=80=99t look great either. T=
he 352 fund has something like $255 million of assets under management, and=
 apparently $107 million of that is in WaterStation bonds? (Which went into=
 default this month.) Was that =E2=80=A6=C2=A0allowed? Chirico was the mana=
ger of the fund, but it is part of Leucadia, which is part of Jefferies, an=
d it is a bit embarrassing that his bosses were not keeping a closer eye on=
 him. The lawsuit says
  [1]
:Throughout this period, Chirico never disclosed his personal conflicts of =
