An extremely simple business model, which we discuss a lot around here, is:=
=09Found a company that makes something cheap. Make (or buy and resell) wid=
gets that cost you $1.=09Sell it at a high price, say $10 per widget.=09Go =
to customers and say =E2=80=9Clook, I know I am selling you a $1 widget for=
 $10 and that doesn=E2=80=99t make sense. But I will pay you $11 to buy the=
 widget, so you=E2=80=99ll come out ahead.=E2=80=9D=09Customers say =E2=80=
=9Csure that sounds good,=E2=80=9D and you get lots of customers.=09The cus=
tomers write checks for $10, payable to your company, which books $10 of re=
venue and $9 of profit ($10 of revenue minus $1 of cost of goods sold).=09Y=
ou write the customers checks for $11, out of your personal account (or the=
 account of another business).=09Economically, you are losing=C2=A0$2 per w=
idget (the $1 it costs to make it, plus the $11 it costs to bribe the custo=
mer, minus $10 of revenue), but the split is +$9 for your company and -$11 =
for your personal account.=09Go to investors and say =E2=80=9Chi, my compan=
y has lots of customers and revenue,=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s growing fast, and it=
=E2=80=99s profitable,=E2=80=9D would you like to buy some?=09Sell 10% of y=
our company to investors=C2=A0at a multiple of like 30 times=C2=A0earnings.=
=09If you sell 1 million widgets a year, that costs you $11 million a year =
in your personal account, but makes $9 million a year for the company. At 3=
0x earnings, that=E2=80=99s a $270 million valuation. If you sell 10% of th=
at, you get $27 million, and you=E2=80=99re ahead by $16 million.=09Then, u=
h. Then=C2=A0you do Step 11.What is Step 11? The good answer is something l=
ike =E2=80=9Cyour idea gets so much traction and so much customer demand, i=
t has such good branding and network effects, that customers now flock to y=
ou to buy your widgets for $10, you don=E2=80=99t have to pay them anymore,=
 and the business remains fast-growing and profitable, but for real now.=E2=
=80=9D This is good for your investors, who bought into a strong and growin=
g company at a $270 million valuation, and for you, because you own the oth=
er 90% of that strong and growing company, which is now worth a lot of mone=
y. (And you=E2=80=99re no longer paying customers out of your personal acco=
unt.)The bad answer is =E2=80=9Cyou do this for a year, you collect your $1=
6 million, you stop paying the customers, the business collapses, the valua=
tion goes to zero and your investors lose their $27 million.=E2=80=9D This =
is bad for your investors, who cashed you out of a worthless business. It i=
s =E2=80=A6=C2=A0not=C2=A0as=C2=A0good for you as building a successful bus=
iness would be, but it is=C2=A0easier, and it does make you a lot of money.=
There are variations on this business model =E2=80=94=C2=A0sometimes the co=
mpany pays the customers directly, because the investors care only about re=
venue growth and not profits; sometimes crypto is involved =E2=80=94=C2=A0b=
ut the basic idea is old and popular. It helps, if you are doing this, to s=
ell something=C2=A0buzzy. A fast-growing ball bearings business is less int=
eresting than a fast-growing ridesharing business, or crypto business, or a=
rtificial intelligence business, or whatever venture capitalists are excite=
d about=C2=A0this year.=C2=A0Carbon credits, for instance:Three years ago, =
Aspiration Partners had turned a debit card designed for sustainable shoppi=
ng and investment accounts that promised complete exclusion of fossil-fuel =
stocks into a high-flying climate startup. The Los Angeles-based company ha=
d set itself on the verge of a stock market debut with an expected valuatio=
n of more than $2 billion. =E2=80=A6But today Aspiration is struggling to s=
tay afloat and faces an investigation by US authorities, including the Depa=
rtment of Justice and the Securities and Exchange Commission. The inside st=
ory of the unraveling of this once-promising climate company comes down to =
its hurried effort to start a new business line=E2=80=94and boost its reven=
ues=E2=80=94by selling sustainability services, such as tree planting, to o=
ther companies.In late 2020, just as company executives began holding meeti=
ngs about a potential public offering, Aspiration signed its first deals wi=
th corporate clients. Within a year, this new unit leapt to more than half =
of Aspiration=E2=80=99s sales=E2=80=94accounting for $56 million of the $10=
0 million in revenues it reported for 2021. But the explosive growth in Asp=
iration=E2=80=99s new business was driven in part by dubious deals that inf=
lated the company=E2=80=99s revenue, according to a Bloomberg Green investi=
gation that relied on interviews with 28 former employees and several of As=
piration=E2=80=99s corporate customers, as well as a review of numerous int=
ernal company documents.Aspiration seems to have been a carbon credit resel=
ler =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmost of these agreements involved reselling ref=
orestation services performed by others, at a very high markup=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and you can guess how the dubious deals worked:An unusual numbe=
r of customers were Colombian celebrities, including an actor and several r=
etired soccer players. Two of them told Bloomberg Green that they had signe=
d agreements simultaneously with Apogee Pacific LLC=E2=80=94an entity that =
was controlled by Joseph Sanberg, Aspiration=E2=80=99s co-founder, board me=
mber and a major shareholder=E2=80=94which would cover the costs they were =
supposed to pay Aspiration.=E2=80=9CIt sounded very weird,=E2=80=9D says Ju=
an Pablo Llano, a Colombian actor who signed deals with both Aspiration and=
 Apogee Pacific, but never exchanged funds with either company. =E2=80=9CI =
smelled something I didn=E2=80=99t like.=E2=80=9DOr there is a Colombian mo=
del who =E2=80=9Csigned a letter of intent in English, which stated, in par=
t, that her nonprofit foundation would pay Aspiration a monthly sum of $50,=
000, allowing her to say she had planted 50,000 trees,=E2=80=9D and who sim=
ultaneously signed a contract with Apogee Pacific that =E2=80=9Cwould pay L=
oaiza $55,000 per month for =E2=80=98marketing and branding services=E2=80=
=99 and would =E2=80=98last for as long as=E2=80=99 she worked with Aspirat=
ion.=E2=80=9D Paying $55,000 for $50,000 of revenue=C2=A0sounds=C2=A0like a=
 bad investment, but if it gets you to a $2 billion initial public offering=
 it could be worth it.
