One very funny model of OpenAI is that it is a nonprofit organization with =
an independent board of directors whose only duties are to its mission =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cbuilding safe and beneficial artificial general intell=
igence for the benefit of humanity=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and not to its i=
nvestors. Those investors are not really shareholders, are explicitly told =
to think of their investments =E2=80=9Cin the spirit of a donation,=E2=80=
=9D and have no rights to elect or remove directors. The board is in charge=
, pursuing only its mission, with no concern for the interests of investors=
.There was like a weekend last year=C2=A0when it looked like that model mig=
ht be correct, and that was a fun time. OpenAI=E2=80=99s board fired its ch=
ief executive officer, Sam Altman, apparently thinking that he was good for=
 investors but bad for humanity. Eventually, though, Altman came back, much=
 of the board left, and the investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0led by Microsoft Corp.=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0asserted their power.An alternative model of OpenAI is that=
 it is a totally normal corporation, with a powerful CEO and employees paid=
 in stock, but everyone has to=C2=A0use slightly different words for antitr=
ust reasons: If Microsoft is in fact a big shareholder of a big AI company,=
 US and European antitrust regulators will have questions, so Microsoft has=
 to instead be a big non-shareholder of=C2=A0a big AI nonprofit. We talked =
last year about how OpenAI=E2=80=99s website once had an org chart describi=
ng Microsoft as a =E2=80=9Cminority owner=E2=80=9D of its for-profit subsid=
iary, but then changed the chart to refer to Microsoft=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cm=
inority economic interest.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9COwner=E2=80=9D bad, =E2=80=9Ce=
conomic interest=E2=80=9D fine.=C2=A0Anyway here=E2=80=99s the latest on th=
at:Microsoft Corp. and Apple Inc. dropped plans to take board roles at Open=
AI in a surprise decision that underscores growing regulatory scrutiny of B=
ig Tech=E2=80=99s influence over artificial intelligence.Microsoft, which i=
nvested $13 billion in the ChatGPT creator, will withdraw from its observer=
 role on the board, the company said in a letter to OpenAI on Tuesday, whic=
h was seen by Bloomberg News. Apple was due to take up a similar role, but =
an OpenAI spokesperson said the startup won=E2=80=99t have board observers =
after Microsoft=E2=80=99s departure.Regulators in the US and Europe had exp=
ressed concerns about Microsoft=E2=80=99s sway over OpenAI, applying pressu=
re on one of the world=E2=80=99s most valuable companies to show that it=E2=
=80=99s keeping the relationship at arm=E2=80=99s length. =E2=80=A6OpenAI s=
aid that moving forward, the company will host regular stakeholder meetings=
 with partners and investors, including Thrive Capital and Khosla Ventures,=
 =E2=80=9Cto share progress on our mission and ensure stronger collaboratio=
n across safety and security.=E2=80=9DMicrosoft won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0observe =
the board meetings, it will just go to the regular stakeholder meetings, co=
mpletely different thing, no antitrust problem here!
