<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Water =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Ponzi =E2=80=A6=C2=A0?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/36014507.198406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDctMDkvamVmZmVyaWVzLWJhY2tlZC1mdW5kLWFjY3VzZXM=
tZXgtcG9ydGZvbGlvLW1hbmFnZXItb2YtZnJhdWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDcxMDI0X01PTkVZU1RVRk=
YmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNzEwJ=
nV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB11ab6a50" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
a fun one</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A hedge fund tha=
t=E2=80=99s part of Jefferies Financial Group sued its former portfolio man=
ager, claiming he orchestrated an investment of more than $100 million in a=
 Ponzi-like scam.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fund, 352 Capital, fi=
led a lawsuit last week against Jordan Chirico, saying he directed the purc=
hase of a large quantity of bonds issued by a company that claimed to opera=
te thousands of filtered water vending machines. According to the suit, Chi=
rico knew these machines didn=E2=80=99t exist but put 352=E2=80=99s money i=
n the scheme in part to recoup his own investment.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Chirico, who earlier this month joined restaurant chain FAT Brands =
Inc. as its head of debt capital markets, referred comment to his lawyer. T=
he lawyer, Bob Gage, didn=E2=80=99t immediately respond to a request for co=
mment.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The water machine company, WaterStat=
ion Management, and several people associated with it, including founder Ry=
an Wear, were also sued by 352. Neither Wear nor WaterStation could be reac=
hed for comment.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36014507.198406/aHR0cHM=
6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3I3ejBGT0F6Wl=
hFOC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd04928fc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the complaint</a>, whic=
h is just wild. 352=E2=80=99s theory is that WaterStation has =E2=80=9Cbeen=
 operating a Ponzi scheme for years,=E2=80=9D involving water vending machi=
nes:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Water Station Management a=
nd another Wear-owned company, Creative Technologies, held themselves out a=
s the manufacturer, operator and manager of thousands of=C2=A0self-service =
water station machines, known as WST-700s, which filter water from a local =
source for purchase by consumers (the =E2=80=9CWater Machines=E2=80=9D). ..=
. Water Station Management also sold =E2=80=9Cfranchises,=E2=80=9D or =E2=
=80=9Cjoint ventures,=E2=80=9D under which third-party investors could purp=
ortedly purchase Water Machines that would be placed and managed by Water S=
tation Management for a fee, with the remaining revenue generated by the ma=
chines being paid to the investors. Wear and Water Station Management also =
agreed to guarantee to some franchisees a =E2=80=9Ctoo good to be true=E2=
=80=9D fixed return of as much as 28% on their investments in lieu of payme=
nts tied to fluctuating revenues.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">You give WaterStation money and it gives you a fixed return of 28%. Whe=
re does it get the money to pay your 28% returns? WaterStation=E2=80=99s an=
swer is apparently =E2=80=9Cfrom selling lots of filtered water to customer=
s,=E2=80=9D but 352 suggests that the answer is =E2=80=9Cfrom new investors=
, like a Ponzi scheme.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Actually 35=
2=E2=80=99s proposed explanation is far more baroque than that.=C2=A0Its st=
ory is that=C2=A0the franchisees got their payments not (just) from new fra=
nchisees but from=C2=A0a $100 million bond offering. And the main buyer of =
the bonds was 352 Capital, which bought the bonds because its portfolio man=
ager was secretly also a WaterStation franchisee who wanted to get his Ponz=
i payments and who saw his own fund=E2=80=99s clients as the best way to ge=
t the money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 352=E2=80=99s telling, Jord=
an Chirico, who managed the 352 fund for Leucadia Asset Management (a divis=
ion of Jefferies), was also a WaterStation franchisee, having invested some=
 $7 million of his own money (through a vehicle called C3 Capital) in 700 W=
aterStation franchises in 2018, before he joined Leucadia. He joined Leucad=
ia in 2020 to start the 352 fund, investing in asset-backed securities. And=
 in 2022, =E2=80=9CChirico arranged for the 352 Fund and its affiliate to i=
nvest in Water Station Management through a bond offering.=E2=80=9D In this=
 offering, WaterStation sold $56.3 million of Class A bonds to another inve=
stor (Heartland Financial), and $15 million of Class B bonds to 352. The mo=
ney was supposed to be used to acquire more water machines, and the machine=
s would be collateral for the bonds.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Chirico allegedly didn=E2=80=99t tell anyone at Jefferies that he was a Wat=
erStation franchisees. Also his friends and family were franchisees.=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9CWater Station Management failed to make payments with regard to th=
ese Chirico-related franchise holdings,=E2=80=9D and so =E2=80=9CChirico pe=
rsonally paid them a total of $300,000 for the purpose of servicing their d=
ebts and discouraging them from commencing litigation against Water Station=
 Management and Wear.=E2=80=9D Also somehow =E2=80=9CKaiwing Fung (=E2=80=
=98Fung=E2=80=99), the former Head of Credit for the 352 Fund, also failed =
to adequately disclose that he owned Water Station Management franchises at=
 the time of the 352 Fund=E2=80=99s investment.=E2=80=9D Chirico led =E2=80=
=9Ca three-person (later four-person) team=E2=80=9D at 352, and two of them=
 were also WaterStation franchisees.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway=
 the money allegedly did not go to buy water machines:</p><blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By no later than August 2023, REVL [Capital Managem=
ent, the collateral manager for the bond]=C2=A0knew that thousands of Water=
 Station Machines allegedly purchased with the bond proceeds did not exist =
and that millions of dollars of bond proceeds had not been used by Water St=
ation Management for their intended purpose. REVL attempted to perform a ph=
ysical inspection of the machines that Water Station Management claimed bot=
h to own and to use as collateral for the bonds. REVL determined that 163 o=
f the 164 machines in its sample set for inspection did not exist. REVL the=
n discovered that more than 3,000 machines that were supposed to be operati=
ng in Family Dollar stores, and=C2=A0in other locations, were =E2=80=9Cactu=
ally missing.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There was =
(or should have been) no doubt, by at least August 2023, that Water Station=
 Management was perpetrating a fraud. To this point, Water Station Manageme=
nt had been submitting to REVL purchase orders and invoices for the purchas=
e of Water Machines, all to convince REVL to authorize the release of bond =
proceeds for those purchases=E2=80=94but those machines did not exist. The =
purchase orders and invoices were falsified. The collateral and revenue rep=
orts that purported to show the machines were installed and generating reve=
nue were likewise fabricated. On information and belief, instead of purchas=
ing and operating Water Machines, Water Station Management used the bond pr=
oceeds primarily to pay =E2=80=9Cfranchisees=E2=80=9D their guaranteed retu=
rns on their =E2=80=9Cinvestment,=E2=80=9D or to buy out franchisees who ha=
d raised complaints about the business=E2=80=94a classic Ponzi scheme. Beca=
use Chirico was owed money in connection with his =E2=80=9Cinvestment=E2=80=
=9D in the scheme, and his friends and family were likewise =E2=80=9Cinvest=
ors,=E2=80=9D he stood to directly, personally benefit from these payouts.<=
/p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Seems bad.=C2=A0But =E2=80=9CR=
EVL only reported what it discovered to Wear and Chirico,=E2=80=9D which ma=
kes a sort of sense: WaterStation was the debtor, 352 was the creditor, and=
 if WaterStation was defrauding 352 then the people to notify would be Wate=
rStation and 352. It=E2=80=99s just that the=C2=A0<em>person=C2=A0</em>at 3=
52 who got the notification was allegedly in on the scheme.=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Actually that is oversimplified: There was another c=
reditor involved, Heartland Financial, who owned the Class A bonds and who =
does not seem to have anything to do with the alleged scheme. That was inco=
nvenient for the alleged Ponzi, so Chirico allegedly had 352=C2=A0<em>buy t=
hem out:</em></p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then, in December=
 2023, despite being fully aware of the ongoing fraud at Water Station Mana=
gement, Chirico made the inexplicable decision to cause the 352 Fund and it=
s affiliate to buy out the Class A bondholder at a purchase price of $57.6 =
million. There was no legitimate business or investment rationale for quadr=
upling the exposure of the 352 Fund to Water Station Management when Chiric=
o knew that Water Station Management was committing a fraud, and that the b=
onds were undercollateralized by tens of millions of dollars (if not more).=
 On information and belief, one contributing factor to Chirico=E2=80=99s de=
cision was to remove any oversight by the Class A investor, which would all=
ow him to loosen the indenture=E2=80=99s restrictions and requirements for =
the benefit of Water Station Management, and direct further funds from the =
352 Fund to Water Station Management to prop up the failing company and the=
 ongoing Ponzi scheme.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, ri=
ght,=C2=A0that is how a Ponzi works: There are always some investors who wa=
nt their money back, or who get suspicious, or who=C2=A0<em>might=C2=A0</em=
>get suspicious, and the way to solve that problem is to raise some money f=
rom new investors to kick out the suspicious ones. And Chirico had access t=
o a good supply of new investors: He ran a=C2=A0bond fund that could provid=
e the money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Somehow Jefferies has Chirico=
=E2=80=99s texts with his wife sort of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0saying =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0this?</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Indeed, in a September=
 2023 text message exchange with his wife, who was a co-owner of C3 Capital=
, Chirico expressed that he was =E2=80=9Cpissed at Ryan [Wear]=E2=80=9D bec=
ause =E2=80=9Che=E2=80=99s not going to be able to make our 300k payment on=
 time either from selling C3 so need to address that as well.=E2=80=9D When=
 his wife asked, =E2=80=9CDoes that worry you about the bond deal,=E2=80=9D=
 Chirico responded: =E2=80=9CYes for bond deal <strong><em>but I care as mu=
ch or more about the personal investors that are with him still </em></stro=
ng>=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D (Emphasis added).</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Still needed more money though:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">By no later than January 2024, Water Station Management was inso=
lvent and unable to meet basic day-to-day funding obligations, including ma=
king payroll. REVL had confirmed that thousands of Water Machines that were=
 supposed to have been purchased with bond proceeds were =E2=80=9Cmissing.=
=E2=80=9D In a January 2024 telephone call with Wear and his CFO, [Tyler] S=
adek, Chirico (who recorded the call) acknowledged that the 352 Fund=E2=80=
=99s $87.9 million bond investment was undercollateralized by at least $46 =
million. On that call, Sadek admitted this was =E2=80=9C<strong><em>the lar=
gest franchise fraud in the history of the United States</em></strong>=E2=
=80=9D and told Wear that he =E2=80=9C<strong><em>was going to jail</em></s=
trong>.=E2=80=9D Notwithstanding his having knowledge of the fraud, and on =
information and belief in furtherance of that fraud, Chirico directed the 3=
52 Fund to upsize the bond offering and, in February 2024, provided Water S=
tation Management with an additional $19 million of funds.=C2=A0</p></block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you do a due diligence call with a co=
mpany, and the company=E2=80=99s chief financial officer tells=C2=A0its chi=
ef executive officer, on a recorded line, that he is going to jail,=C2=A0an=
d you hear that and your reaction is=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe need to buy even more=
 of those bonds=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean part of me wants to say =E2=
=80=9Cyou are a bold contrarian risk-taker and a lot of asset managers woul=
d want to hire you.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s coolness under pressure right t=
here. But yes another possibility is that you are in on the scam.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you believe 352=E2=80=99s allegations, then obvio=
usly WaterStation and Chirico look bad, but Jefferies and Leucadia don=E2=
=80=99t look great either. The 352 fund has something like <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36014507.198406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2=
VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NTcyNTQvMDAwMTg1NzI1NDI0MDAwMDAxL3hzb=
EZvcm1EWDAxL3ByaW1hcnlfZG9jLnhtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa435f28b" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">$255 million of assets under management</a>, and apparently $107 million =
of that is in WaterStation bonds? (Which went into default this month.) Was=
 that =E2=80=A6=C2=A0allowed? Chirico was the manager of the fund, but it i=
s part of Leucadia, which is part of Jefferies, and it is a bit embarrassin=
g that his bosses were not keeping a closer eye on him. The lawsuit says<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Throughout this period, C=
hirico never disclosed his personal conflicts of interest to the 352 Fund, =
that Water Station Management was committing fraud, that the Water Machines=
 securing the bonds largely did not exist, or that he was directing the 352=
 Fund to substantially increase its exposure while it was already undercoll=
ateralized by tens of millions of dollars. Chirico deliberately provided va=
gue and misleading explanations for increasing the 352 Fund=E2=80=99s posit=
ions and for changes to the indenture=E2=80=99s terms to convince the 352 F=
und=E2=80=99s investment manager, and other stakeholders, to =E2=80=9Csign =
off=E2=80=9D on those changes, while withholding critical information that =
would have caused any rational investment manager to cease contributing to =
the Water Station Management scheme and take immediate action to protect in=
vestors.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still seems weird. I =
guess if you run an asset management firm and one of your portfolio manager=
s wants to quadruple his allocation to some water-machine-backed bonds, you=
r first thought will not be =E2=80=9Cperhaps this water machine company is =
a Ponzi scheme, and our portfolio manager is involved in it.=E2=80=9D Just =
seems like running a bond fund at Leucadia is a=C2=A0<em>better=C2=A0</em>j=
ob than being a franchisee of a water filtration Ponzi scheme, so you=E2=80=
=99d expect him to prioritize his bond-investing job over his water-Ponzi j=
