#ccc;">here</a>, is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left=
: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Found a compa=
ny that makes something cheap. Make (or buy and resell) widgets that cost y=
ou $1.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sell it at a high price, sa=
y $10 per widget.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Go to customers =
and say =E2=80=9Clook, I know I am selling you a $1 widget for $10 and that=
 doesn=E2=80=99t make sense. But I will pay you $11 to buy the widget, so y=
ou=E2=80=99ll come out ahead.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">Customers say =E2=80=9Csure that sounds good,=E2=80=9D and you get lot=
s of customers.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The customers writ=
e checks for $10, payable to your company, which books $10 of revenue and $=
9 of profit ($10 of revenue minus $1 of cost of goods sold).</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You write the customers checks for $11, out of y=
our personal account (or the account of another business).</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Economically, you are losing=C2=A0$2 per widget (t=
he $1 it costs to make it, plus the $11 it costs to bribe the customer, min=
us $10 of revenue), but the split is +$9 for your company and -$11 for your=
 personal account.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Go to investors=
 and say =E2=80=9Chi, my company has lots of customers and revenue,=C2=A0it=
=E2=80=99s growing fast, and it=E2=80=99s profitable,=E2=80=9D would you li=
ke to buy some?</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sell 10% of your c=
ompany to investors=C2=A0at a multiple of like 30 times=C2=A0earnings.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you sell 1 million widgets a year, =
that costs you $11 million a year in your personal account, but makes $9 mi=
llion a year for the company. At 30x earnings, that=E2=80=99s a $270 millio=
n valuation. If you sell 10% of that, you get $27 million, and you=E2=80=99=
re ahead by $16 million.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then, uh.=
 Then=C2=A0you do Step 11.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is St=
ep 11? The good answer is something like =E2=80=9Cyour idea gets so much tr=
action and so much customer demand, it has such good branding and network e=
ffects, that customers now flock to you to buy your widgets for $10, you do=
n=E2=80=99t have to pay them anymore, and the business remains fast-growing=
 and profitable, but for real now.=E2=80=9D This is good for your investors=
, who bought into a strong and growing company at a $270 million valuation,=
 and for you, because you own the other 90% of that strong and growing comp=
any, which is now worth a lot of money. (And you=E2=80=99re no longer payin=
g customers out of your personal account.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
The bad answer is =E2=80=9Cyou do this for a year, you collect your $16 mil=
lion, you stop paying the customers, the business collapses, the valuation =
goes to zero and your investors lose their $27 million.=E2=80=9D This is ba=
d for your investors, who cashed you out of a worthless business. It is =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0not=C2=A0<em>as=C2=A0</em>good for you as building a successful=
 business would be, but it is=C2=A0<em>easier</em>, and it does make you a =
lot of money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are variations on this =
business model =E2=80=94=C2=A0sometimes the company pays the customers dire=
ctly, because the investors care only about revenue growth and not profits;=
 sometimes <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3601450=
7.198406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMT=
